---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Principles" description="The five design principles Groundwork is built on">
  <section class="gw-section">
    <div class="gw-width gw-prose">
      <h1 class="gw-heading-l">Principles</h1>
      <p>
        Five principles shape every API and token decision in Groundwork. Component and pattern pages cite
        them by name in their Background sections so the reasoning behind a decision stays traceable to the
        thing it serves.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m" id="constraints-produce-consistency">Constraints produce consistency</h2>
      <p>
        The spacing scale has intentional gaps. There is no value between 24px and 32px. This is a feature —
        it eliminates the decision between 26, 28, and 30. You pick 24 or 32 and move on. The principle
        applies everywhere: two border radii, not five. Three ink colours, not seven. Four border widths that
        cover every structural use case.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m" id="names-describe-decisions">Names describe decisions, not appearances</h2>
      <p>
        <code class="gw-mono">--ink-secondary</code> tells you <em>when</em> to use it (supporting text).
        <code class="gw-mono">--ink-muted</code> tells you what it <em>looks like</em> (muted) and leaves you
        guessing whether it is for hints, disabled states, or metadata. Every token name should pass the
        rename test: can you change the underlying value without the name becoming a lie?
      </p>
      <p>
        The same rule applies at the component layer. A Button variant is
        <code class="gw-mono">destructive</code>, not <code class="gw-mono">red</code>, so re-theming the
        variant is a token swap rather than a rename across every call site.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m" id="accessibility-is-structural">Accessibility is structural, not aspirational</h2>
      <p>
        The React <code class="gw-mono">&lt;Field&gt;</code> component requires a label prop. It is not a
        lint warning or a documentation note — it is a type error. Error messages are structured into
        <code class="gw-mono">{`{ problem, fix }`}</code> so the component API guides you toward the pattern
        that helps users recover. The focus ring is 3px solid yellow — ugly on purpose, unmissable by design,
        and identical across every interactive element so consistency does the work attention cannot.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m" id="css-is-the-product">The CSS is the product, React is the enforcement layer</h2>
      <p>
        The token system and component styles work as a standalone CSS file. Groundwork can be applied to
        plain HTML or any framework by attaching class names. The React layer's job is narrower: make the
        correct patterns the only patterns available through the component API. TypeScript turns the design
        rules into type constraints.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m" id="progressive-disclosure">Progressive disclosure of complexity</h2>
      <p>
        Start with <code class="gw-mono">&lt;Field&gt;</code>, <code class="gw-mono">&lt;Input&gt;</code>,
        and <code class="gw-mono">&lt;Button&gt;</code>. That covers most forms. Add error handling when you
        need it. Add summary lists for review pages. Add banners and choice groups as the surface grows. The
        system is designed so you can be productive on day one without holding the whole component set in
        your head.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
